% ===== Page 3 =====
\subsection{Comments}

\begin{itemize}
\item What binning to use:
\begin{itemize}
\item[--] Linear or no binning for homogeneous data (``bell-shaped'', Gaussian, binomial, Poisson);
\item[--] Logarithmic for heterogeneous data (power laws).
\end{itemize}

\item Number of bins:
\begin{itemize}
\item[--] Is usually such that all bins are statistically significant;
\item[--] In most real-world power-law networks $\mathcal{B} \in [15, 25]$;
\item[--] If unsure, set $\mathcal{B} = 20$.
\end{itemize}

\item If asked to average over many (random) graphs from the same ensemble, collect all the data $(x_j, (y_j))$ from \textit{all} the generated graphs \textit{as if it was one huge graph}. That is:
\begin{itemize}
\item[--] concatenate data in the following format: $(i, k_i, c_i, k_{nn,i})$ --- RIGHT;
\item[--] NOT in the following format: $(k, n(k), c(k), k_{nn}(k))$ --- WRONG!
\end{itemize}

\item The correct Python implementations of the described binning procedures are available
\begin{itemize}
\item[--] for functions in \texttt{scipy.stats.binned\_statistic()} with the \texttt{statistic} parameter set to \texttt{'mean'} (the default);
\item[--] for distributions in \texttt{numpy.histogram()} with the \texttt{density} parameter set to \texttt{True}.
\end{itemize}

\end{itemize}

